'''Kirstie Louise Alley''' (born January 12, 1951) is an American actress and comedian known for her role in the TV series ''[[Cheers]]'', in which she played [[Rebecca Howe]] from 1987 to 1993, winning an [[Emmy Award]] and a [[Golden Globe Award]] as the Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series in 1991. She is also known for her role in the thriller ''[[Shoot to Kill (1988 film)|Shoot to Kill]]'' and the ''[[Look Who's Talking]]'' film series as Mollie Ubriacco. More recently, Alley has appeared in reality shows revolving around her life.

==Early life==
Kirstie Alley was born in [[Wichita, Kansas]], the daughter of Lillian Mickie (née Heaton), a homemaker, and Robert Deal Alley, who owned a lumber company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/542/000023473|title=Kirstie Alley|publisher=Soylent Communications|accessdate=November 9, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodhousekeeping.com/family/celebrity-interviews/kirstie-alley-may07|title=Kirstie Alley Recharged|publisher=[[Good Housekeeping]]|date=May 2007|accessdate=June 3, 2012}}</ref> She has two siblings, Colette and Craig. Alley attended [[Wichita Southeast High School]], graduating in 1969.<ref name="CNN Transcripts">[http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0504/15/pzn.01.html ''Paul Zahn Now''], April 15, 2005.</ref> She attended college at [[Kansas State University]] in 1969.<ref name="CNN Transcripts"/> After moving to Los Angeles to pursue [[Scientology]] and work as an [[interior design]]er, she appeared as a contestant on the popular game show ''[[Match Game]]'' in 1979, where she won multiple games.<ref name="hstern">Interview with Kirstie Alley, ''[[The Howard Stern Show]]'', December 4, 2013.</ref> She also appeared on the game show ''[[Password Plus]]'' in 1980. In 1981, a car accident caused by a drunk driver killed her mother and left her father seriously injured. Her father eventually recovered.<ref name="CNN Transcripts"/>

==Career==
Alley made her movie debut in 1982 in ''[[Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan]]'', playing the Vulcan Starfleet officer Lieutenant [[Saavik]]. In 1987, she joined the cast of ''[[Cheers]]'', replacing [[Shelley Long]] and remaining on the show until its eleventh and final season.<ref name="hstern"/> In 1989, Alley starred with [[John Travolta]] in ''[[Look Who's Talking]]'', the film grossed over $295,000,000 worldwide. They then went on to make two other films centered around the same theme, ''[[Look Who's Talking Too]]'' and ''[[Look Who's Talking Now]]!''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lookwhostalking.htm |title=Look Who's Talking (1989) |publisher=Box Office Mojo |date=1990-03-06 |accessdate=2013-12-04}}</ref>

Alley has won two [[Emmy Award]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/celebrities/kirstie-alley |title=Kirstie Alley &#124; Academy of Television Arts & Sciences |publisher=Emmys.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-04}}</ref> during her career. Her first two nominations for her work on ''[[Cheers]]'' did not earn her the award, but her third, in 1991, garnered her the statuette for that series. In her speech, she thanked then-husband [[Parker Stevenson]], calling him "the man who has given me the big one for the last eight years."<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Kp3knpyugZ8&t=1m06s |title=43rd Annual Emmys - Kirstie Alley |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref>

For contributions to the motion picture industry, Alley was honored with a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] at 7000 [[Hollywood Boulevard]].<ref name="HWOFDB">{{cite web|url=http://www.hwof.com/stars?recipient=Kirstie_Alley|title=Hollywood Walk of Fame database |publisher=HWOF.com}}</ref>

Alley played the title character in the NBC sitcom ''[[Veronica's Closet]]'', as well as serving as executive producers on the show. She served as the spokesperson for [[Pier One]] from 2000–04 and for [[Jenny Craig]] from 2005–08.

[[TV Land]] aired a sitcom that centered on Alley as a [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] star and a new parent. It was titled ''[[Kirstie (TV series)|Kirstie]]'', and reunited her with former ''[[Cheers]]'' co-star [[Rhea Perlman]] and ''[[Seinfeld]]'' star [[Michael Richards]]. The series premiered on December 4, 2013,<ref>{{cite web|title=TV Land greenlights Kirstie Alley comedy|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-kirstie-alley-tv-land-comedy-20130215,0,4699671.story|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=15 February 2013}}</ref> and ran for one season before it was canceled, five months after ending its freshman run.<ref>{{cite web|title=TV Land cancels 'Kirstie'|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/07/29/kirstie-canceled-tv-land/|publisher= Entertainment Weekly and Time Inc.|accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref>

===''Dancing with the Stars''===
{{Main|Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 12)|Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 15)}}
In February 2011, Alley was announced as a contestant on ''[[Dancing with the Stars]]''. She was partnered with [[Maksim Chmerkovskiy]]. Their first dance, a [[cha-cha-cha (dance)|cha-cha-cha]], earned them the second-highest score, 23 points of a possible 30. On May 2011, Alley and Chmerkovskiy performed their final dance, also a cha-cha-cha, which earned them a perfect score of 30 out of 30. Alley finished the competition in second place, behind [[NFL]] [[Super Bowl]] champion [[Hines Ward]]. She also took part in the [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 15)|15th season]] of ''Dancing with the Stars'' for a second chance to win the mirrorball trophy<ref>{{cite web|last=Shira |first=Dahvi |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20615549,00.html |title=Dancing with the Stars: Joey Fatone, Bristol Palin in All-Star Cast |publisher=People.com |date=2012-07-27 |accessdate=2013-12-04}}</ref> again with Maksim Chmerkovskiy. They were the seventh couple eliminated from the competition.

==Personal life==
Alley met and dated a distant cousin, Bob Alley, in high school. They married in 1970. Her husband had the same name as her father.,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://starcasm.net/archives/181573 |title=All about Kirstie Alley's first marriage and love affairs |publisher=starcasm.net |date=2012-11-07 |accessdate=2013-12-04}}</ref> but they divorced seven years later as their career paths diverged.<ref>{{cite web|title=Star Magazine Uncovers Dancing With The Stars Celebs’ Secret Pasts|url=http://kearth101.radio.com/2011/03/31/star-magazine-uncovers-dancing-with-the-stars-celebs-secret-pasts|publisher=[[KRTH]]|accessdate=April 5, 2011}}</ref> Alley was married to her second husband, [[Parker Stevenson]] (Richard Stevenson Parker, Jr.) on December 22, 1983. They divorced in 1997. Alley and Stevenson share custody of their two children, William True and Lillie Price.<ref>{{cite web|title='Gal-imony': Celeb Women Who Pay in the Divorce|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/CelebrityCafe/story?id=7356641&page=2|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=July 4, 2010}}</ref>

===Weight gain===
On September 17, 2012, Alley appeared on ''[[The Dr. Oz Show]]'' where she admitted that she started gaining weight in late 2003. Alley claimed she spent her whole life eating obsessively without gaining weight, and only noticed a change in her body after she went into early menopause in 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheredcarpet.com/Kirstie-Alley-opens-up-about-weight-gain-on-Dr--Oz/8814220|title=Kirstie Alley opens up about weight gain on 'Dr. Oz'|work=OTRC|accessdate=September 17, 2012}}</ref>

===Weight loss===
In March 2010, Alley launched Organic Liaison, which includes Rescue Me, the first [[USDA]]-certified organic weight loss product. She announced that she lost {{convert|100|lbs|kg}} using the program in September 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20530210,00.html|title=Kirstie Alley's New Life 100 Lbs. Lighter!|work=People|accessdate=September 21, 2011}}</ref>

===Scientology===
Alley was raised as a [[Methodist]], but has been a member of the [[Church of Scientology]] since 1979.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2364389/Scientologist-Kirstie-Alley-posts-cryptic-tweet-Leah-Remini-makes-dramatic-exit-Church-I-thought-friend.html |title='I thought she was my friend... f*** her': Staunch Scientologist Kirstie Alley posts cryptic tweet as Leah Remini makes dramatic exit from Church |publisher=Daily Mail |date=15 July 2013 |accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref> At the time she became a [[Scientologist]], Alley admitted to having had a [[cocaine]] addiction and went through [[Narconon]], a Scientology-affiliated drug treatment program,<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.cs.cmu.edu/~dst/Narconon/safety.htm| title = Narconon Exposed: Is Narconon safe?| date = November 5, 2002| publisher=''Carnegie Mellon’s School of Computer Science''}}</ref> to end her dependency.<ref>{{cite news |first=Kari |last=Huus |title=Scientology’s love affair with Hollywood |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/8333804/ |publisher=[[MSNBC]] |date=July 5, 2005 |accessdate=September 12, 2009}}</ref> She has continued her Scientology training and, as of 2007, had attained the level of OT VII ([[Operating Thetan]] level 7).<ref name="OT7">{{cite episode | title = Scientology and Me | episodelink = Scientology and Me | series = Panorama | serieslink = Panorama (TV series) | network = [[BBC One]] | airdate = May 14, 2007}}</ref>

In May 2000 she purchased a {{convert|5200|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} waterfront mansion from fellow Scientologist [[Lisa Marie Presley]] for $1.5 million. The house is in [[Clearwater, Florida]], the spiritual headquarters of the Church of Scientology. In 2007 Alley gave $5 million to the Church.<ref>Associated Press. "Scientologists' big donations," ABC Action News, Scripps TV Station Group, January 30, 2008. Retrieved on January 31, 2008.</ref>

After celebrity [[Leah Remini]] left the Church of Scientology in 2013, Alley publicly denounced Remini as a "a repulsive bigot" and declared her former friend was now "my enemy".<ref>http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2519060/Kirstie-Alley-slams-Leah-Remini-Howard-Stern.html</ref>

